vulnerability_information:
DiffieHellman doesn't generate keys after setting a key

## Steps To Reproduce:

  1. Instantiate: `const dh = crypto.createDiffieHellman(1024);`
  2. Set private key: 
```
//set private key to 2
dh.setPrivateKey(Buffer.from("02", 'hex'));        
//outputs 02 (as expected)
console.log(dh.getPrivateKey().toString('hex'));  
```
  3. Generate random private key:
```
//generate random private key
dh.generateKeys();                                 
//outputs 02: zero day.
console.log(dh.getPrivateKey().toString('hex'));   
```

## Underlying issue:

OpenSSL (https://github.com/majek/openssl/blob/master/crypto/dh/dh_key.c) doesn't generate keys when they're already instantiated: 

```
if (dh->priv_key == NULL)
  {
  priv_key=BN_new();
  if (priv_key == NULL) goto err;
  generate_new_key=1;
  }
else
  priv_key=dh->priv_key;

if (dh->pub_key == NULL)
  {
  pub_key=BN_new();
  if (pub_key == NULL) goto err;
  }
else
  pub_key=dh->pub_key;
```

node:crypto should use OpenSSL correctly. Method `generateKeys()` should re-instantiate OpenSSL before requesting a key, thereby avoiding the above.

## Impact

DiffieHellman may be used as the basis for application level security, implications are consequently broad. E.g., key reuse can cause major problems, cryptanalysis may break confidentiality, integrity, ...

activities.message:
Thanks for the report @bensmyth. The (legacy) DH/ECDH APIs are relatively thin wrappers around OpenSSL and do have some significant design issues, and some of those are certainly not documented well. [I added `crypto.diffieHellman()` a while ago as a modern alternative](https://github.com/nodejs/node/pull/31178) but it likely does not cover all low-level use cases.

IIRC, `generateKeys()` only generates _missing_ (or outdated) keys, that is, it only generates a private key if none has been set yet, but the function is also needed to compute the corresponding public key after calling `setPrivateKey()`.

```js
const crypto = require('crypto');
{
  const dh = crypto.createDiffieHellman(1024);
  // Both the private and the public key are missing: generateKeys() generates both.
  dh.generateKeys();
}
{
  const dh = crypto.createDiffieHellman(1024);
  dh.setPrivateKey(Buffer.from('01020304', 'hex'));
  // Only the public key is missing: generateKeys() generates only the public key.
  dh.generateKeys();
}
{
  const dh = crypto.createDiffieHellman(1024);
  dh.generateKeys();
  // Neither key is missing: generateKeys() does nothing.
  dh.generateKeys();
}
{
  const dh = crypto.createDiffieHellman(1024);
  // Both the private and the public key are missing: generateKeys() generates both.
  dh.generateKeys();
  dh.setPrivateKey(Buffer.from('01020304', 'hex'));
  // The public key is outdated: generateKeys() generates only the public key.
  dh.generateKeys();
}
```

A similar design issue is that `getPublicKey()` will return a stale public key if you call `setPrivateKey()` without a subsequent `generateKeys()`.

`DiffieHellmanGroup` behaves similarly (and is usually preferable over `DiffieHellman`). It is also much faster, so there is usually no need to reuse `DiffieHellmanGroup` instances. (`DiffieHellman` used to be fast enough to not be reused, but is now somewhat slow due to expensive parameter validation.)

> Method `generateKeys()` should re-instantiate OpenSSL before requesting a key, thereby avoiding the above.

Unless I'm missing something, your proposed solution would break applications that use `generateKeys()` to generate the public key that corresponds to a known private key.

I am not quite sure yet how we can best address these design issues. These APIs have been around for a long time and should likely be deprecated eventually, unless we can significantly improve their design without breaking too many existing applications.
